==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Cessation
<hw>Ces*sa"tion</hw> <pr>(s⟦ecr⟧s*s⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>cessation</ets>, L. <ets>cessatio</ets>, fr.
<ets>cessare</ets>. See <er>Cease</er>.]</ety> <def>A ceasing or
discontinuance, as of action, whether temporary or final; a stop;
<as>as, a <ex>cessation</ex> of the war</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The temporary <qex>cessation</qex> of the papal iniquities.</q>
<rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The day was yearly observed for a festival by <qex>cessation</qex>
from labor.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cessation of arms</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>an
armistice, or truce, agreed to by the commanders of armies, to give time
for a capitulation, or for other purposes.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Stop; rest; stay; pause; discontinuance;
intermission; interval; respite; interruption; recess;
remission.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cessavit</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
